Any css or more advanced html stuff will have to wait till I reach a certain point in the Ohmfa project. I will update the masterbin in the next 1-2 days, and tweek the neocities tag catalog as well. Any feedback is greatly appreciated.

>Next time you should elaborate on the story itself next time, try to sell people on it instead of being an anon proclaiming you've helped work on a story and that's why you like it.

Oh that's easy to explain then. I like the basic setup of the two characters and a misunderstanding leading to them knowing one another, of them both having a much more clear personality and way of being, of the way their friendship develops entirely because of their luggage and how that actually does have consequences instead of it being a thing that's mentioned and forgotten, while both being basically made for one another. Mike and Ruby's issues severely affect how the whole thing developed, even despite the very clear attraction and mixed interests, neither of them wanted to ruin what was a good friend at the core and did their best to deny or suppress any romantic intent while still clearly yearning it as much as possible. The main conflict so far of the story has been how Ruby didn't want to feel like she's the last choice, entirely caused by Mike being cautious and not wanting to rush it with Ruby or to make it awkward with a sudden double date to someone like her, the fallout from the failed double date and more causing heartbreak for both that each had to endure, a real conflict.

Ruby felt guilty for hurting him, Mike felt terrible for what he did too, she kept herself responsible. As their relationship grew, so did they as characters, Ruby loosening her barriers and Mike slowly losing his own as they eroded away the things that kept them far apart, all it took was just a "trial" and they're together as they arguably always should have been, the barriers entirely made up as a way to protect themselves from others. Its a tale of two neurotic worrywarts trying not to step on one anothers shoes as they dance a waltz they're desperately trying to pretend they don't want to dance, slowly growing closer with each step.

Its rather beautiful really.

Oh, also the POV changes which are interesting, the way the locations change, the actual thematics and activities being different to most other stories and the reasonably different waifur while still being long but not written like some purple prose time waster. Very little of Roo'd is actually written to waste your time, spending just as long as it needs to for you to know what's going on in the protagonists heads, to know what the scene is and letting you picture it as you see fit. For a story as big as Roo'd, that's a pretty big sign of quality, as it could just be useless meandering fluff which lead nowhere or just to look poetic and fancy, but it restrains itself from ever entering that ballpark.

The mentions of actual Anthro anatomy mattering, the exploring of the Kangaroo one instead of it just being an aesthetic and it remaining quite wholesome throughout is also very nice. Took a while for em to share a bed, but it felt like it was the right thing to happen considering all the buildup from the duo of dorks.
